- Mon 16 Sep 2019. Summary of top news
[Kaiser Daily Global Health Policy Report, abridged, edited]
https://www.kff.org/news-summary/who-ebola-response-running-out-of-money-organization-warns-urges-caution-over-decline-in-outbreak-indicators/

CIDRAP News: WHO urges caution amid Ebola decline in DRC
"Ebola outbreak indicators show promising signs of decline, but it's too soon to tell if the pattern will persist, the World Health Organization (WHO) said [Thu 12 Sep 2019] in its weekly overview of developments in the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC). Meanwhile, 14 new confirmed cases were reported today [13 Sep 2019], lifting the outbreak's overall total to 3113, according to numbers reflected on the WHO's online Ebola dashboard..." (Schnirring, 13 Sep 2019).

The Hill: WHO warns it's running out of money to fight Ebola
"The largest force against the yearlong outbreak of the deadly Ebola virus in Congo says it only has enough money for the fight to last through the end of the month [September 2019]. The World Health Organization (WHO) said Friday [13 Sep 2019] that it has received about USD 55 million from governments around the world since [1 Aug 2019], just one-fifth of the amount it needs to implement a strategic response plan meant to contain the virus through the end of the year..." (Wilson, 13 Sep 2019).

UPI: WHO: Ebola funds not enough to fight virus through end of 2019
"...The organization said it needs USD 287 million to help affiliate groups curtail the virus and at least USD 120 million to keep its own operations going. The money it has received so far is projected to run out by the start of October [2019]. 'Further resources are needed to fund the response through to December 2019, and WHO is appealing to donors to provide generous support,' it said in a statement..." (Hughes, 13 Sep 2019).

