- Mon 16 Sep 2019. No Time to Lose (Peter Piot)
[The Telegraph, abridged, edited]
https://www.telegraph.co.uk/global-health/science-and-disease/greatest-threat-lab-says-scientist-discovered-ebola/
[Byline: Sarah Newey]

It is now more than 4 decades since Professor Peter Piot sped from a clinical lab in the bustling Belgian city of Antwerp to a remote rainforest in the heart of Africa to investigate a mysterious epidemic.

Three weeks earlier the microbiology lab where the then 27-year-old worked had received 2 vials of blood transported halfway across the globe in a cheap blue thermos flask filled with ice.

One of the test tubes had smashed, but at the time in 1976 Professor Piot and his colleagues were unaware of the danger lurking inside. The 2 vials contained a new but highly contagious virus that we now know as Ebola -- a disease that has killed more than 2000 people in a 13-month outbreak in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC).

The blood samples were from Flemish nuns living in what was then known as Zaire, who had died of a mysterious haemorrhagic fever. Within 3 weeks, the virus had killed 200 people in Yambuku, a small village in the Congolese forest home to a Belgian missionary outpost.

"The discovery itself was an accident, or a coincidence," Professor Piot says, sitting in his directors' office at the London School of Hygiene Tropical Medicine, which celebrates its 120th anniversary this autumn [2019].

"We obviously did not know there was Ebola in the samples from Zaire. Looking back, probably the most dangerous moments were working in the lab in Antwerp."

It wasn't long before the team, examining the virus' gigantic worm structure under a microscope, realised this was a new disease and sent the samples to the specialist Centre for Disease Control in the US for confirmation. Within weeks Professor Piot was on a flight -- without so much as a valid passport.

"I'm trying not to exaggerate, but in less than 48 hours I went from Antwerp to the tropical rainforest in northern Zaire," he says. "It was extremely exciting, to be honest."

"I'd never been to Africa, I'd never investigated an epidemic, so I definitely did not qualify and in today's world, I don't think I would be allowed to do this."

As Professor Piot recalls in his book, No Time to Lose, what followed were 2 adventure-filled but exhausting months, predominantly spent in the jungle some 600 miles from Zaire's capital city, Kinshasa. An international team of scientists meticulously investigated the disease, which slowly petered out after killing 280 people.

Instead, Professor Piot thought that outbreaks would be isolated to remote communities with neglected health systems -- in 1976, Ebola was spread when dirty syringes were used.

"But I underestimated the societal amplifiers," says Professor Piot. "I didn't fully appreciate the social, behavioural, political, cultural context that these epidemics thrive in."

In West Africa, Ebola spread for 3 months under the radar before it was detected, by which point it had reached capital cities and slums, making it much harder to control.

"There was the social background of the lack of trust in governments, with countries coming out of civil wars," adds Professor Piot. "And that is what we are seeing now in eastern Congo as well."

[To] bring the outbreak to a close the community needs to be at the centre of the response and a 2nd vaccine should be rolled out to complement the one already in use and the successful new treatment options, Professor Piot says. It won't be easy.

"I think it will be extraordinarily difficult to bring it under control, because of the security environment. The worst case scenario would be that there is an increase in fighting, and then god help us," he says.

And yet, despite his obvious fears about Ebola, it is Disease X -- an as yet unknown pathogen that the World Health Organization has flagged as a priority -- that Professor Piot flags as the greatest infectious threat to humans.

"The biggest concern I have is not Ebola, but a new pandemic flu... that could really kill millions of people, and I'm not scaremongering here.

"With Ebola, mostly the risk here [in the UK] would be for people working in intensive care units. You don't catch Ebola on the bus, on the tube. But the flu, or another new respiratory virus, yes... that's why the world needs to be prepared."

